GO:CC GO:0005840 ribosome "An intracellular organelle, about 200 A in diameter, consisting of RNA and protein. It is the site of protein biosynthesis resulting from translation of messenger RNA (mRNA). It consists of two subunits, one large and one small, each containing only protein and RNA. Both the ribosome and its subunits are characterized by their sedimentation coefficients, expressed in Svedberg units (symbol: S). Hence, the prokaryotic ribosome (70S) comprises a large (50S) subunit and a small (30S) subunit, while the eukaryotic ribosome (80S) comprises a large (60S) subunit and a small (40S) subunit. Two sites on the ribosomal large subunit are involved in translation, namely the aminoacyl site (A site) and peptidyl site (P site). Ribosomes from prokaryotes, eukaryotes, mitochondria, and chloroplasts have characteristically distinct ribosomal proteins." [ISBN:0198506732] 23 4.360984e-20 2

Hence, the prokaryotic ribosome (70S) comprises a large (50S) subunit and a small (30S) subunit, while the eukaryotic ribosome (80S) comprises a large (60S) subunit and a small (40S) subunit. HP

HP HP:0002151 Increased circulating lactate concentration Abnormally increased level of blood lactate (2-hydroxypropanoic acid). Lactate is produced from pyruvate by lactate dehydrogenase during normal metabolism. The terms lactate and lactic acid are often used interchangeably but lactate (the component measured in blood) is strictly a weak base whereas lactic acid is the corresponding acid. Lactic acidosis is often used clinically to describe elevated lactate but should be reserved for cases where there is a corresponding acidosis (pH below 7.35). 5 0.000121 3
HP HP:0001941 Acidosis Abnormal acid accumulation or depletion of base. 5 0.003086 3
HP HP:0004360 Abnormality of acid-base homeostasis An abnormality of the balance or maintenance of the balance of acids and bases in bodily fluids, resulting in an abnormal pH. 5 0.004419 3

HP HP:0001639 Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) is defined by the presence of increased ventricular wall thickness or mass in the absence of loading conditions (hypertension, valve disease) sufficient to cause the observed abnormality. 16 6.205094e-11 4
HP HP:0025354 Abnormal cellular phenotype An anomaly of cellular morphology or physiology. 21 7.548842e-11 4
HP HP:0000817 Reduced eye contact A reduced frequency or duration of eye contact. 12 1.650626e-10 4
HP HP:0034435 Abnormal eye contact Any abnormality of eye contact behavior. We define eye contact as a form of nonverbal communication between two individuals who are facing each other in which an individual directs the eyes towards the eyes or face of the other individual. Eye contact occurs frequently and voluntarily during face-to-face verbal communication. The duration and frequency of eye contact that is interpreted to be appropriate may follow social and situational norms. 12 1.841609e-10 4
HP HP:0000758 Abnormal nonverbal communicative behavior Abnormalities in eye contact, communicative facial expressions, gesture use, or the use of others' bodies to communicate convey shared meanings within a culture that replace or supplement verbal communication. 12 3.477518e-10 4
HP HP:0011015 Abnormal blood glucose concentration An abnormality of the concentration of glucose in the blood. 16 8.656860e-10 4
HP HP:0430071 Abnormal circulating organic compound concentration Any deviation of the concentration of an orrganic compound from the normal range. An organic compound is defined as any compound that contains a carbon atom. 20 1.508604e-08 4
HP HP:0001298 Encephalopathy Encephalopathy is a term that means brain disease, damage, or malfunction. In general, encephalopathy is manifested by an altered mental state. 15 2.363010e-08 4
HP HP:0002352 Leukoencephalopathy This term describes abnormality of the white matter of the cerebrum resulting from damage to the myelin sheaths of nerve cells. 13 4.476773e-08 4
HP HP:0002421 Poor head control Difficulty to maintain correct position of the head while standing or sitting. Infant head lag is observed when the head seems to flop around or lags posteriorly behind the trunk. Several articles have maintained that head lag should be absent by age 3 to 4 months. 13 6.930105e-08 4
HP HP:0002013 Vomiting Forceful ejection of the contents of the stomach through the mouth by means of a series of involuntary spasmic contractions. 15 1.061332e-07 4
HP HP:0002151 Increased circulating lactate concentration Abnormally increased level of blood lactate (2-hydroxypropanoic acid). Lactate is produced from pyruvate by lactate dehydrogenase during normal metabolism. The terms lactate and lactic acid are often used interchangeably but lactate (the component measured in blood) is strictly a weak base whereas lactic acid is the corresponding acid. Lactic acidosis is often used clinically to describe elevated lactate but should be reserved for cases where there is a corresponding acidosis (pH below 7.35). 12 3.737785e-07 4
HP HP:0012337 Abnormal homeostasis An anomaly in the processes involved in the maintenance of an internal equilibrium. 25 6.035958e-07 4
HP HP:0002363 Abnormal brainstem morphology An anomaly of the brainstem. 13 7.095211e-07 4
HP HP:0000618 Blindness Blindness is the condition of lacking visual perception defined as a profound reduction in visual perception. On the 6m visual acuity scale, blindness is defined as less than 3/60. On the 20ft visual acuity scale, blindness is defined as less than 20/400. On the decimal visual acuity scale, blindness is defined as less than 0.05. Blindness is typically characterized by a visual field of no greater than 10 degrees in radius around central fixation. 13 1.138790e-06 4
HP HP:0002921 Abnormal cerebrospinal fluid morphology An abnormality of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). 17 1.781266e-06 4
HP HP:0000543 Optic disc pallor A pale yellow discoloration of the optic disc (the area of the optic nerve head in the retina). The optic disc normally has a pinkish hue with a central yellowish depression. 12 3.317427e-06 4
HP HP:0001638 Cardiomyopathy A myocardial disorder in which the heart muscle is structurally and functionally abnormal, in the absence of coronary artery disease, hypertension, valvular disease and congenital heart disease sufficient to cause the observed myocardial abnormality. 16 3.378383e-06 4
HP HP:0001637 Abnormal myocardium morphology A structural anomaly of the muscle layer of the heart wall. 16 7.089135e-06 4
HP HP:0003808 Abnormal muscle tone Abnormal muscle tone 26 8.116774e-06 4
HP HP:0001942 Metabolic acidosis Metabolic acidosis (MA) is characterized by a fall in blood pH due to a reduction of serum bicarbonate concentration. This can occur as a result of either the accumulation of acids (high anion gap MA) or the loss of bicarbonate from the gastrointestinal tract or the kidney (hyperchloremic MA). By definition, MA is not due to a respirary cause. 10 1.011771e-05 4
HP HP:0002017 Nausea and vomiting Nausea is a commonly encountered symptom that has been defined as an unpleasant painless subjective feeling that one will imminently vomit. Vomiting has been defined as the forceful expulsion of the contents of the stomach, duodenum, or jejunum through the oral cavity. While nausea and vomiting are often thought to exist on a temporal continuum, this is not always the case. There are situations when severe nausea may be present without emesis and less frequently, when emesis may be present without preceding nausea. 15 1.184007e-05 4
HP HP:0034059 Abnormal fetal physiology Any functional anomaly of the fetus. 12 2.533730e-05 4
HP HP:0000745 Abnormal diminished volition A reduction in willful and motivated goal-directed behavior that is considered the determinant of behavior and adaptation that allows individuals to get started, be energized to perform a sustained and directed action. 16 3.402368e-05 4

HP HP:0001952 Glucose intolerance Glucose intolerance (GI) can be defined as dysglycemia that comprises both prediabetes and diabetes. It includes the conditions of impaired fasting glucose (IFG) and impaired glucose tolerance (IGT) and diabetes mellitus (DM). 12 2.320107e-04 4
HP HP:0002240 Hepatomegaly Abnormally increased size of the liver. 15 3.005624e-04 4
HP HP:0011804 Abnormal muscle physiology A functional abnormality of a skeletal muscle. 26 3.930894e-04 4
HP HP:0001252 Hypotonia Hypotonia is an abnormally low muscle tone (the amount of tension or resistance to movement in a muscle). Even when relaxed, muscles have a continuous and passive partial contraction which provides some resistance to passive stretching. Hypotonia thus manifests as diminished resistance to passive stretching. Hypotonia is not the same as muscle weakness, although the two conditions can co-exist. 23 4.570458e-04 4
HP HP:0011400 Abnormal CNS myelination An abnormality of myelination of nerves in the central nervous system. 12 6.924492e-04 4

HP HP:0001324 Muscle weakness Reduced strength of muscles. 17 3.713459e-03 4
HP HP:0001251 Ataxia Cerebellar ataxia refers to ataxia due to dysfunction of the cerebellum. GO:CC GO:0005840 ribosome "An intracellular organelle, about 200 A in diameter, consisting of RNA and protein. Both the ribosome and its subunits are characterized by their sedimentation coefficients, expressed in Svedberg units (symbol: S). Hence, the prokaryotic ribosome (70S) comprises a large (50S) subunit and a small (30S) subunit, while the eukaryotic ribosome (80S) comprises a large (60S) subunit and a small (40S) subunit. Two sites on the ribosomal large subunit are involved in translation, namely the aminoacyl site (A site) and peptidyl site (P site). Ribosomes from prokaryotes, eukaryotes, mitochondria, and chloroplasts have characteristically distinct ribosomal proteins." [ISBN:0198506732] 22 2.715158e-18 2

GO:CC GO:0005840 ribosome "An intracellular organelle, about 200 A in diameter, consisting of RNA and protein. It is the site of protein biosynthesis resulting from translation of messenger RNA (mRNA). It consists of two subunits, one large and one small, each containing only protein and RNA. Both the ribosome and its subunits are characterized by their sedimentation coefficients, expressed in Svedberg units (symbol: S). Hence, the prokaryotic ribosome (70S) comprises a large (50S) subunit and a small (30S) subunit, while the eukaryotic ribosome (80S) comprises a large (60S) subunit and a small (40S) subunit. Two sites on the ribosomal large subunit are involved in translation, namely the aminoacyl site (A site) and peptidyl site (P site). HP HP:0002151 Increased circulating lactate concentration Abnormally increased level of blood lactate (2-hydroxypropanoic acid). Lactate is produced from pyruvate by lactate dehydrogenase during normal metabolism. The terms lactate and lactic acid are often used interchangeably but lactate (the component measured in blood) is strictly a weak base whereas lactic acid is the corresponding acid. Lactic acidosis is often used clinically to describe elevated lactate but should be reserved for cases where there is a corresponding acidosis (pH below 7.35). 5 0.000704 3

HP HP:0002151 Increased circulating lactate concentration Abnormally increased level of blood lactate (2-hydroxypropanoic acid). Lactate is produced from pyruvate by lactate dehydrogenase during normal metabolism. The terms lactate and lactic acid are often used interchangeably but lactate (the component measured in blood) is strictly a weak base whereas lactic acid is the corresponding acid. Lactic acidosis is often used clinically to describe elevated lactate but should be reserved for cases where there is a corresponding acidosis (pH below 7.35). 5 0.000121 0
HP HP:0001941 Acidosis Abnormal acid accumulation or depletion of base. 5 0.003086 0
HP HP:0004360 Abnormality of acid-base homeostasis An abnormality of the balance or maintenance of the balance of acids and bases in bodily fluids, resulting in an abnormal pH. 5 0.004419 0
HP HP:0003128 Lactic acidosis An abnormal buildup of lactic acid in the body, leading to acidification of the blood and other bodily fluids. 4 0.007771 0
